We have written a testing tool based on the junit framework and are 
having trouble extending it to support our needs. We rely heavily on 
TestSuites for our test reporting and the current version of 
junit.framework does not allow for accurate test reporting when 
multiple suites reference the same TestCase class. My current dilemma 
has to do with running the ActiveSuite decorator.

Upon examining swingui I found the following method in 
junit.swingui.TestTreeModel:
**
* Tests if the node is a TestSuite.
*/
TestSuite isTestSuite(Object node) {
if (node instanceof TestSuite) 
return (TestSuite)node;
if (node instanceof TestDecorator) { 
Test baseTest= ((TestDecorator)node).getTest(); 
return isTestSuite(baseTest); 
} 
return null;
}

What I would like to see is a model where the TestListener interface 
recognised the start and end of each suite and each Test instance 
knows which suite it belongs to so we can report accurate results 
even when running multiple threads.


Below is sample code to illustrate my point. Try running in swingui 
or Eclipse runner.

package xpunit.misc.test;

import junit.extensions.ActiveTestSuite;
import junit.extensions.RepeatedTest;
import junit.framework.Test;
import junit.framework.TestCase;
import junit.framework.TestSuite;

public class ActiveRepeatedSuiteTest extends TestCase {
	static boolean oscillator = false;
	public ActiveRepeatedSuiteTest(String name) {
		super(name);
	}

	public void testMultipleFailures() throws Exception {
		if(oscillator) {
			oscillator=false;
			fail(&quot;oscillator is true&quot;);
		}
		else oscillator=true;
	}

	static public Test suite() {
		ActiveTestSuite s = new ActiveTestSuite(&quot;Active 
Suite&quot;);
		TestSuite s1 = new TestSuite(&quot;s1&quot;);
		s1.addTestSuite(ActiveRepeatedSuiteTest.class);
		TestSuite s2 = new TestSuite(&quot;s2&quot;);
		s2.addTestSuite(ActiveRepeatedSuiteTest.class);
		TestSuite s3 = new TestSuite(&quot;s3&quot;);
		s3.addTestSuite(ActiveRepeatedSuiteTest.class);

		s.addTest(s1);
		s.addTest(s2);
		s.addTest(s3);

		return new RepeatedTest(s,3);
	} 

}

